  "text": "Iflca~h) is inactivated by rising [Ca2+]i, it should be possible to modify this process by enhancing the Ca 2+ buffering capacity of the cytoplasm. Fig. 6 shows the consequences of injecting Paramecium iontophoreticaUy with the Ca 2+ chelator, EGTA. A -7-nA, 15-s injection ([EGTA]i ~ 1.4 mM) consistently increased the amplitude of both/peak and 1300 (Fig. 6 B) , but only slightly. In some cells EGTA injection affected the time course of decay of/Ca(h)\" For example, a 300-ms step to -130 mV before EGTA injection elicited a current that inactivated biphasically, with time constants of 8 and 151 ms. After EGTA injection, an identical step elicited a current that decayed monoexponentially (~ = 51 ms). Increasing [EGTA]i to ~ 4.2 mM (-7 hA, 45 s) failed to affect Ica~h) amplitude or decay rates further; at levels in excess of 5 raM, cell condition deteriorated rapidly (not shown). We also injected cells with BAPTA, which chelates Ca 2+ with greater efficiency than EGTA [CITATION_1] . Moderate injections (-7 nA, 5 s) increment /peak and Is00 to an extent similar to EGTA, but BAPTA injections are considerably more lethal (not shown), perhaps indicating that cell survival is critically dependent on a basal level of [Ca2+]i. ",
